You’ll find this in various guises and various names across the Balkans and Eastern Europe, Greece and Turkey, all the way to Armenia and North Africa….. it’s the Borek Belt! 😂

It’s made with all sorts of filling options, but for me, I can’t go past lamb. The spices are intoxicating (cinnamon is the secret!), and I adore the pine nuts / currants combo.

For a veg option, use the filling from my Spana recipe - it’s so good!! - N x ❤️

PS To make the Melb Queen Victorian Markets Borek version, just shape into individual size logs instead of spiral, same bake time.👌🏻

Borek – with Spiced Lamb (Turkish version)

INGREDIENTS:
FILLING: 2 tbsp olive oil, 1 onion finely diced,  2 garlic cloves finely minced, 600g / 1.2 lb lamb mince (sub beef), 1 1/2 tsp ground cumin, 3/4 tsp EACH ground coriander, cinnamon, paprika,  1/2 tsp allspice (sub mixed spice), 1/2 tsp cayenne pepper, 1/2 tsp black pepper,  1 1/4 tsp cooking / kosher salt,  1/3 cup currants (or similar), 1/3 cup pine nuts toasted,  1 cup tomato passata (tomato puree in US), 1/4 cup water
YOGURT WASH FOR FILO (STOPS CRACKING) - mix: 1 egg, 2 tbsp plain yogurt, 30g / 2 tbsp unsalted butter melted
PASTRY: 12 sheets phyllo pastry, 25g / 1 1/2 tbsp unsalted butter melted and cooled,  White sesame seeds (optional)
LEMON YOGURT SAUCE - mix: 1 cup plain yogurt, 1/4 tsp garlic finely grated, 1 tbsp lemon juice, 1 tbsp extra virgin olive oil,  Pinch of salt

DIRECTIONS
1. Filling: Heat oil on high, cook onion & garlic 2 min, add lamb, cook until changes from pink to brown. Add all spices, cook 1 min. Add everything else, stir, simmer on low 5 min until liquid mostly evaporated, but still juicy. Fully cool.
2. Flick yogurt wash onto filo then lightly brush (don’t need to cover every inch). Repeat for 4 layers (don’t brush top layer). Roll with 1/3 of lamb. Repeat to make 3 rolls. Roll into spiral on paper (use yogurt wash to connect). Slide into butter greased 26cm / 10.5″ cast iron skillet (or freeform on tray). Brush with butter, sprinkle with sesame seeds. Bake 200°C / 390°F (180°C fan) 40 min until golden. Cut wedges like pie, serve with yogurt sauce!

If I can do it with my chubby little hands, it’ll be a breeze for you! As for what to make with it? Coming later today. IT’S EPIC!!!
.
UPDATE: to those raising concerns, putting it in the freezer is a humane way to dispatch a crab. It goes into a coma, no mental or physical activity, so feels nothing when you break it up. The other way is to spike it through central nerves. But you can miss. Freezer is easier. I did a lot of research on this topic.
.
Full directions step by step are on my website - https://www.recipetineats.com/how-to-clean-and-cut-a-whole-crab/
.

You'll love how the cake is lovely and moist (too often they are terribly dry!), and how it’s not too sweet so you can actually taste all the elements. Looks rich and decadent, but is actually not that rich at all – so you can eat plenty! 😋 - N x ❤️
.
PS I specifically use jarred cherries NOT fresh. They're softer so texturally they make more sense, plus the flavoured syrup from the jar is perfect to brush the cake layers. Just not the same using fresh cherries! 

Black Forest Cake
.
CHOC CAKE: 6 large eggs (room temp), 1 tsp vanilla, 1 1/4 cup caster/superfine sugar, 1/2 cup dutch processed cocoa powder (or regular), 2/3 cup plain/all-purpose flour, 150g/10.5 tbsp unsalted butter (melted cooled)
CHERRY SYRUP: 670g / 23.5 oz pitted morello cherries in syrup (sour cherries, jar or can) , drained & juice reserved, 1/3 cup kirsch or cherry liqueur (sub more cherry syrup), 1/2 cup caster /superfine sugar, 4 tsp cornflour/cornstarch
CREAM - whip: 4 cups/1 litre thickened/heavy cream, 2 tsp vanilla, 1/3 cup soft icing sugar / powdered sugar.
DECORATING: 100g / 3.5 oz dark/bittersweet chocolate to make curls, 12 maraschino or fresh cherries
.
1. Sift flour & cocoa, set aside. Beat eggs 30 sec speed 6. Add sugar over 45 sec with beat on, then add vanilla. Beat 7 min on speed 8, tripled volume pale white. Fold in flour/cocoa, then fold in butter. Bake 25 min 180°C / 350°F (160°C fan) in 3 x 20cm (8”) cake pans (greased & lined). Cool 10 min then cool on racks.
2. Mix ¼ cup cherry juice with cornflour. Dissolve sugar in another 1/3 cup cherry juice in saucepan over med heat. Add cornflour slurry, simmer 1 min until thin syrup. Add to cherries, cool.
3. Brush 3 tbsp syrup on cake, spread with 1 cup cream, top with half cherries. Top with cake, then repeat syrup > cream > cherries. Top with cake, brush with ¼ cup syrup, cover cake with cream. Pipe cream swirls around edge, top with cherries. Pile choc curls in centre. Leave 4 hrs in fridge to overnight before serving! Keeps 3 - 4 days.
.

I promise I take constructive criticism well. 😇 - N x ❤️
.
Turkish Pide (Flat bread / Turkish Pizza)
.
DOUGH (MAKES 2): 1 tsp rapid rise / instant yeast (sub active dry yeast), 1/2 tsp white sugar, 2 tbsp + 2/3 cups very warm water, 2 cups bread flour (sub all purpose/plain), 3/4 tsp salt, 1 1/2 tsp olive oil
ASSEMBLING: 150g / 5oz Turkish kasar cheese or mozzarella, 1/2 tsp semolina (optional)
SPINACH TOPPING: 2 tsp olive oil, 1/2 onion finely diced, 280g/10oz baby spinach, 1/2 tsp EACH cumin, pepper, 1/4 tsp salt
TURKISH SAUSAGE TOPPING (SUJUK): 125g / 4oz Turkish Sujuk sausage (sub chorizo)
LAMB TOPPING: 1 tbsp olive oil, 1/2 onion finely diced, 1 garlic clove finely minced, 250g / 8oz lamb mince (or beef), 1 tsp tomato paste, 1 tsp Baharat spice mix, 1/2 tsp cumin, 1/8 tsp each salt & pepper, 1/2 red capsicum / bell pepper & 1/2 tomato finely chopped, 1 tsp lemon juice
SPRINKLING FINISHES – CHOOSE: 4 tbsp Turkish Tulum cheese or feta (crumbled), dried oregano, Sesame seeds toasted, Sumac, Coriander/cilantro leaves, Extra virgin olive oil
.
1. DOUGH: Mix yeast w/2 tbsp water + sugar, stand 10 min until foamy. Mix with flour, salt and olive oil, knead 8 min until smooth (stand mixer 3 min speed 6). Rise 1.5 hrs until doubled in size. Punch down, halve, shape into balls, rise on floured tray covered with damp tea towel.
2. ASSEMBLE: Roll out into 40 x 20cm / 16 x 8” oval shape, sprinkle tray with semolina. Place dough on, sprinkle with cheese & topping of choice, leaving 2 cm/ 0.8” border. Brush end with water, pinch to seal, then fold sides in. Bake 15 min at 240°C/465°F (220°C fan). (EGG OPTION – crack on top when 5 min bake time left). Sprinkle with Finishes of choice (any combo works!), cut into slices & serve! 
3. SPINACH: Heat oil medium high, cook onion, wilt spinach, stir in seasonings.
4. SAUSAGE: Blitz to turn into mince, then crumble across pide surface.
5. LAMB: Heat oil medium high, cook onion and garlic, cook lamb, add everything else and cook until all liquid evaporates (3 – 5 min).
.

That moment when he blows out the candles…😂😂😂
.
HAPPY BIRTHDAY DOZER!!! - N x ❤️
.
DOZER’S 9TH BIRTHDAY CAKE!! 🎉🎂
.
Whipped potato might sound like a weird frosting, but it looks and behaves like buttercream frosting and DOGS don’t care!!! 
.
DOG Friendly BIRTHDAY CAKE:
2 eggs, 1/2 cup (120g) peanut butter (spread or pure), 1/4 cup oil (canola, veg)
2/3 cup milk (or water), 1/3 cup honey or maple syrup (or apple sauce or skip it), 2 1/2 cups shredded carrot (2 large), 2 cups (300g) whole wheat / wholemeal or white flour (plain/all purpose), 2.5 tsp baking soda
DOG FRIENDLY FLUFFY FROSTING (WHIPPED POTATO YOGURT): 1 kg / 2 lb potatoes , peeled, cut into chunks, 1 cup yogurt (plain unsweetened) or water, blue gel colouring (I used Sky Blue by Wilton) or food colouring
DRIP FROSTING: 1/2 cup cornflour/cornstarch, 1/4 cup plain yogurt, 1 – 2 tbsp milk (as needed)
.
1. Whisk eggs, peanut butter, oil, milk and honey. Stir in carrot, then flour and baking soda until JUST incorporated.
2. Divide between 2 x 15cm/6” pans that are 7.5cm/3” deep (grease and line). Bake 180C/350F (160C fan) for 30 min or until skewer comes out clean. Cool on rack, trim top to make it flat, then cut each cake in half.
3. Cook potato until VERY soft (boil, steam, microwave). Whip with yogurt plus extra water to achieve soft, spreadable consistency.
4. Spread ~2/3 cup frosting between each layer. Then colour the remaining frosting with your desired colour (I did 2 x toothpick dips into gel/ smear on surface of mash). Frost cake.
5. Mix Drip Frosting ingredients, do a test consistency – should drip slowly down vertical side. Spread frosting on top of cake first, then use teaspoon to make drips. Decorate with silver balls etc as desired then refrigerate immediately to set Drip Frosting. Store in fridge until ready to serve!!
.

Bake with me! Hear the story of ANZAC Day - and take a moment to remember those who fought and lost their lives for us.
.
Lest We Forget. - Nagi & Dozer 🌹
.
Anzac Biscuits
.
1 cup (150g) plain flour
1 cup (100g) rolled oats
1 cup (80g) desiccated coconut
3/4 cup (165g) white sugar , preferably caster / superfine
150g / 5oz unsalted butter
4 tbsp golden syrup (sub 1 tbsp light molasses OR treacle plus 3 tbsp honey)
1 tsp baking soda (bicarbonate soda)
.
DIRECTIONS
1. Mix flour, oats, coconut and sugar.
2. Melt butter with golden syrup over medium heat. Once it starts bubbling, add the baking soda. Stir to dissolve - it will foam!
3. Pour into flour mixture, mix until combined.
4. Scoop up 1 tbsp of mixture, roll into ball then flatten into a thinnish patty (they don’t spread much). For standard size you buy in packets at the supermarket, use 2 tsp of mixture.
5. Place on paper lined trays 2.5cm/1” apart. Bake 15 min at 180C/350F (160C fan) for crisp ANZAC biscuits or until deep golden, or 12 minutes or until golden for chewy centres.
6. Cool 5 min on tray then transfer to cooling racks. They will be soft when warm but will crisp up when cooled. Crispy ones stay crispy for a week in an airtight container, after that they soften but still super tasty. Also can crisp up in oven – 5 min at same temp!
.
For more detailed directions, including step & ingredient photos and a full video recipe tutorial, please see the recipe on my website - search “Anzac biscuits” on www.recipetineats.com (link in bio)
.

Bringing some French sophistication to your weekend in the form of Crème Brûlée! So very tres chic, so very easy, this is quite possibly the king of all custards. Ultra smooth, velvety and rich yet somehow also delicate at the same time, this is a fab elegant dessert for dinner parties because it’s make ahead. So you can totally nail the poised-dinner-host thing. If you’re into that sort of thing. Me - I try. But as you’ve seen over the years on IG stories, I start off the cook looking poised and end up a sweaty frightful mess. 😂 - N x ❤️
.
Crème Brûlée
.
2 cups pure cream (Aus) / heavy cream (US)
1 vanilla pod OR 1 tsp vanilla bean paste
5 egg yolks 
1/4 cup caster sugar (superfine sugar)
TOFFEE TOPPING: 2 tsp caster sugar (superfine sugar)
.
1. Scrape vanilla bean seeds out of vanilla pod. Put the seeds, used pod and cream in a saucepan, simmer on low heat 10 min. Remove from stove, stand 1 hour uncovered. Remove bean and scoop off any skin formed on surface. 
2. Whisk yolks and sugar in a bowl until just combined. Stir in cream – don’t overstir, we don’t have bubbles in our custard.
3. Divide between 4 x 150ml / 2/3 cup ramekins. Place in baking pan, fill with boiling water up to halfway. Bake 35 minutes at 130°C/265°F (120°C fan) – should be set (ie not water) but still jiggles when you gently shake it. 
4. Cool then refrigerate 6 hrs (up to 3 days). Sprinkle with sugar, blast with blow torch to melt and caramelise. Serve immediately. OR put under super hot broiler/grill 1 min, the fridge 20 min – 1 hr, then serve.

.

I’m going to call it - this is the most delicious Cauliflower recipe I know. Big, BIG call - but I’m standing by it!!
.
This is a pretty common side you’ll find at high end steakhouses or a particularly lavish Sunday roast. It’s unapologetically indulgent, intended to replicate the luxury you’d expect from such establishments! So while it’s not the same, you can cut calories by switching the cream for milk, and reducing some of the cheese (I can’t believe I just wrote that🙀) 
.
Be on theme - try it alongside steak or any seared protein, or roast chicken, beef, pork or lamb. Devour and be prepared to swoon…. - N x ❤️
.
Cauliflower Cheese (Bake/Gratin)
.
ROASTED CAULIFLOWER (SO much tastier than boiling!):
1kg / 2 lb cauliflower florets (1.25 / 2.5lb whole 1 very large head, 1 1/2 medium or 2 small)
2 tbsp extra virgin olive oil
1/2 tsp sea salt
1/8 tsp pepper
CHEESE SAUCE (MORNAY SAUCE):
60g / 4 tbsp unsalted butter
30g / 3½ tbsp flour , plain / all-purpose
1 cup milk (full fat best) + 1 cup cream (or more milk), heated until hot but not boiling
1/2 tsp cooking salt (kosher salt)
1/4 tsp nutmeg powder (freshly grated is best)
100g / 1 cup Red Leicester cheese (or cheddar, or other melting cheese), grated
50g / ½ cup gruyère cheese , grated (or other melting cheese of choice)
TOPPING: 1/2 cup (50g) EACH Red Leicester cheese and Gruyere
.
1. Toss cauliflower in salt, pepper and oil. Bake 220C/430F (200C fan) for 20 min, no turning. Should be slightly undercooked still, with a bit of colour. 
2. Meanwhile, melt butter in small pot or large saucepan over medium heat. Add flour, stir 3 min. Pour in half milk while stirring, then once it’s mostly lump free, stir in remaining milk. Use whisk if needed to remove lumps. Cook 1 min – should be thick enough to coat wooden spoon (see vid). Turn off stove (but keep pot on stove), stir in cheese, salt and nutmeg. Should be thick but pourable.
3. Add cauliflower, stir to coat. Transfer mixture to a 2L / 2qt baking dish (30 x 20 x 5cm / 12 x 8 x 2"). Top with cheese, bake 180C/350F 30 min until bubbly and golden (all oven types). Sprinkle with parsley, serve!

.

Weekend cooking project!! Well, one of them 😊 I have another one for you tomorrow!
.
Introducing the little sister of the famous Beef Pho - Chicken Pho! Equally delicious, but sooo much easier to make. 👌🏻 - N x ❤️
.
Chicken Pho (4 big servings, 6 light servings)
.
CHARRED AROMATICS: 1 tbsp oil, 2 onions halved (skin on), 5cm/ 2" piece of ginger , sliced 0.75cm / 1/3" thick (unpeeled)
PHO SOUP BROTH:
2 litres / 2 quarts water
1.5 kg / 3 lb chicken thighs, bone in skin on  OR whole chicken
1 small bunch coriander/cilantro, 5 star anise pods, 1 cinnamon stick, 4 cloves, 2 tsp EACH fennel & coriander seeds, 8 tsp fish sauce, 6 tsp white sugar, 1/2 tsp salt
BOWLS: 
360g / 13 oz dried rice noodles, thin flat (or 600g fresh)
2 green onions stems , finely sliced
TOPPINGS - HELP YOURSELF: 3 cups bean sprouts, 1 small bunch EACH Thai Basil, min, coriander/cilantro*, 2 limes, Hoisin sauce, Sriracha, Red chillies finely sliced (optional)
.
1. Heat oil in 6 litre/6 quart+ pot over high heat. Place onion & ginger cut face down, leave 2 min until black, turn leave 2 min.
2. Add all Broth ingredients EXCEPT salt. Bring to simmer, then put lid on leaving it open a crack, adjust heat so it’s simmering gently. Scoop off foam once or twice, simmer 1.5 hrs.
3. Remove chicken (shred meat), then strain into new pot. Should be 1.5 litres/1.5 quarts – measure, simmer to reduce or add water to top up. 
4. Add 1/2 tsp salt into broth – taste. Should be slightly salty (dilutes when served over noodles etc). Keep it piping hot while you prepare Toppings.
5. Prepare noodles per packet, drain very well, immediately put in bowls. Top with some chicken, ladle over broth, sprinkle with green onions. Serve like that, let people put everything else on themselves!

.

Red Velvet is so much more than the scarlet coloured crumb! True to its name, they are more “velvety” than typical cupcakes, with a hint of vanilla and chocolate flavour. And that cream cheese frosting is everything! - N x ❤️

Red Velvet Cupcakes

INGREDIENTS:
DRY – SIFT together: 1 1/3 cups cake flour (sub plain / all purpose flour)
1 tbsp cocoa powder (unsweetened), 1 1/2 tsp baking powder, Pinch of salt
WET:
 60g / 4 tbsp unsalted butter softened, 2/3 cup caster sugar (superfine sugar), 2 large eggs (room temp), 1/3 cup veg or canolia oil, 1/2 cup buttermilk (room temp), 1 tsp vanilla extract, 1/2 tsp white vinegar, 1 tbsp red food colouring (yes, 1 whole tablespoon!)
CREAM CHEESE FROSTING: 1/3 cup unsalted butter , softened, 170g / 6oz Philadelphia block cream cheese softened (NOT TUB, too soft), 1/2 tsp vanilla extract, 1/8 tsp salt,  2 1/2 cups soft icing sugar mixture (powdered sugar), sifted

1. Cupcakes: Beat butter 1 min, add sugar then beat 2 min until fluffy and smooth. Beat in eggs one at a time. Then add remaining Wet ingredients, beat just until smooth.
2. Scatter sifted Dry ingredients across surface, beat for 20 sec, scrape down sides, beat further 10 sec just until smooth – few small lumps ok, better than over beating (makes cupcakes tough).
3. Divide between 12 lined muffin tin holes, bake 20 min at 180C/350F (160C fan) or until skewer inserted in middle comes out clean. Remove onto rack immediately and cool completely before frosting.
4. Cream Cheese Frosting – Beat butter 1 min, add cream cheese, beat 1 min. Add icing sugar in 4 batches, beating in between starting on low to avoid dust storm in your face! Add vanilla and salt, now BEAT BEAT BEAT for 2 min until fluffy and creamy. Transfer to piping bag and use immediately. (Note: If butter or cream cheese too soft, frosting will get sloppy, in which case, fridge 20 min, beat again, then use)

It is ridiculous how big that slab of brisket looks compared to my chubby little hands…😂

Size aside, this is excellent low effort, big batch food that’s good for days ’n days. Pile onto rolls with your favourite fixings! - N x ❤️

SLOW COOKER BEEF BRISKET with BBQ Sauce | Serves 8 - 10

The BBQ Sauce has a mild tingle of spiciness from the black pepper and cayenne pepper. Adjust the cayenne pepper to reduce spiciness.

Rub:
1 tbsp brown sugar + 2 tsp paprika + 1/2 tsp cumin + 3/4 tsp mustard powder
1 tsp EACH onion powder, garlic powder
1 tsp salt + 1/2 tsp black pepper
Beef:
1.5 – 2 kg / 3 – 4 lb beef brisket
BBQ Sauce:
2 garlic cloves minced, ½ cup apple cider vinegar
1 1/2 cups ketchup, 1/2 cup brown sugar
2 tsp EACH black pepper, onion powder, mustard powder
1 tsp cayenne pepper, 1 tbsp Worcestershire sauce

1. Mix Rub, rub all over brisket. If time permits, leave for 30 min – 24 hours in the fridge, but I rarely do this (it essentially marinades during slow cooking).
2. Combine BBQ Sauce ingredients in a slow cooker. Mix, add the brisket.
3. Slow cook in slow cooker for 8 hrs (1.5 kg / 3 lb) to 10 hrs (2 kg / 4 lb). 
4. Remove brisket, pour liquid in slow cooker into a saucepan. Bring to simmer over medium high heat and reduce until it thickens to a syrup consistency.
5. Meanwhile, roast brisket in 200C/390F oven for 15 min until brown spots appear. Base with Sauce, return to oven for 5 min. Baste again, then return to oven for 5 – 10 min until caramelised. 
6. TO SERVE: Slice brisket thinly across the grain and serve with remaining BBQ Sauce. Pile high onto rolls with Coleslaw or dinner plate with cornbread and Slaw! (Recipes for all sides on my site)

**see the full recipe on my website for oven and pressure cook directions.

#recipetineats #brisket #slowcookerrecipes

Butter basting looks and feels totally pro. But actually, it’s more than just about showing off! 😂 It’s about flavour - think of the butter seeping into all the cracks and crevices - and more even cooking thanks to the bubbling butter being spooned over the salmon.

Try it. You’ll never look back! - N x ❤️

PS You probably won’t use all the butter for serving. Don’t waste it - it’s flavour loaded. Scrape into a bowl, keep for up to 4 days. Use to pan fry slices of bread another night. OUTRAGEOUSLY good! See photo in this recipe on my website.

Garlic Butter Salmon – Cheffy way!
.
4 salmon fillets (180g/6oz each), skinless and boneless
1/2 tsp salt , cooking / kosher, 1/4 tsp black pepper
1 1/2 tbsp olive oil
90g / 6 tbsp salted butter , cut into cubes (or unsalted + 1/4 tsp salt)
1 tbsp garlic, finely minced by hand (don't use a garlic press)
1 tsp lemon juice, plus more to taste
2 tsp parsley, finely chopped
.
1. Sprinkle salmon with salt and pepper. Heat oil in a non stick pan over medium high heat. Add salmon presentation side down, cook 3 min. Turn, cook 1 min.
2. Add butter, once it melts and is foaming, add garlic. Then immediately tilt the pan slightly so the butter pools on one side and start spooning the foaming butter over the salmon. Do this for 1 ½ minutes for medium rare (optimum juiciness that restaurants serve salmon at, internal temp 50°C/122°F). 
3. Remove salmon from pan, leave to rest for 3 min. Return pan to turned off stove, add lemon juice. Serve salmon with butter sauce, sprinkle with parsley. Pictured in video with Cauflilower Puree (recipe on website).

This pot of khaki coloured sludge might not look like much. But this ugly duckling packs a PUNCH in the delicious department!!!

One of the few “throw it all in the slow cooker” recipes I have. No need to saute onion beforehand – you’ll find it rises to the surface and essential self sautes in the ham fat. 🙌🏻 - N x ❤️

Pea and Ham Soup (slow cooker or stove)

500g / 1lb dried split peas 
1.2-1.5kg / 2.4-5lb ham hock (aka ham bone), bacon hock or MEATY leftover ham bone 
1/4 tsp salt (start with less, adjust later), 3/4 tsp black pepper, 2 garlic cloves minced, 2 bay leaves (dried or fresh), 1 onion, 2 celery sticks and 1 carrot finely chopped, 8 cups (2 litres/qts) water
.
1. Place peas in slow cooker, push ham in. Scatter all ingredients around the ham bone, then pour over water.
2. Slow cook 8 to 10 hours on LOW or 6 hours on HIGH. (Or 2.5 hours on low on stove, 1 h - 1 hr 20 min pressure cooker/Instant Pot on HIGH)
3. Remove ham bone, shred ham meat. Discard bone and fatty skin.
4. Remove bay leaves. Use a stick blender to blitz 2 or 3 times - thickens soup but doesn't make it completely smooth (my preference, you can blend completely if you want).
5. Return ham into slow cooker, stir. Taste and add more salt if needed (soup gets lots of salt from ham). Serve garnished with parsley. Serve with crusty bread for dunking - the famous No Knead Artisan Bread, quick Irish Soda Bread, Garlic Bread or upgrade to Cheesy Garlic Bread! {All on my site}

#recipetineats #slowcookerrecipe #peahamsoup #wintercomfort

So, this is a copycat of a popular salad at a charcoal chicken chain in Sydney called Chargrill Charlies. Their chicken is meh. But they actually have decent salads. This is one of their most popular ones. It costs $7 for a tiny tub!! It’s offensively expensive. So I made a copycat! - N x ❤️

PS I can hear my friends rolling their eyes thinking “she never complains about the price of Spicy Asian food, but here she is complaining about the price of a salad”. Well, yeah! Spicy Asian v Salad? No contest.🤷🏻‍♀️

Chargrill Charlie’s Green Bean Salad with Creamy Avocado Dressing

SALAD
500g / 1 lb green beans , cut into 5cm / 2" pieces, steamed until soft (5 min microwave steamer)
3 tomatoes , cut into thin wedges
1 avocado (large, or 2 medium) , diced into 1.5cm / 2/3" pieces
1/2 red capsicum / bell pepper diced, 1/2 red onion finely diced

Creamy Avocado Dressing - Blitz the following ingredients until smooth:
1/2 cup ripe avocado (smush into cup to measure, or estimate - 1/2 medium avo), 3 tbsp extra virgin olive oil, 3 tbsp sour cream or yogurt (Greek or plain, unsweetened), 2 tbsp lemon juice, 1 garlic clove, small , minced using garlic crusher, 4 tbsp water (to thin out, it's very rich!), 1/2 tsp salt, 1/4 tsp black pepper

Taste then adjust: salt, pepper, lemon and oil to taste, and use water to adjust thickness (avos differ in density) – you want it just pourable, not a thick gloop, but not so thin it’s watery (bland and tasteless). Keeps 3 days (switch fresh garlic for powder, keeps 5 days).

SALAD DIRECTIONS: 
Toss with half the Avo Dressing, then serve with extra dressing on side. PRESENTATION NOTE: Not as pretty once tossed so if you want it to look nice, then take to table with dressing drizzled across top, then toss when serving (this is a presentation trick restaurants use)

#recipetineats #beansalad #avocadorecipe #healthy

So much more than just a giant hunk of meat in loaf form…. Well, that is, if it’s DONE RIGHT! 😂 

How’s the music choice on this one?? 🎶 - N x ❤️

PS Leftovers make excellent sandwiches. Slather light toasted bread slices or warm soft rolls with butter and ketchup, top with warm slice of meatloaf. 👌🏻 (Don’t ruin with greens)

Meatloaf | Serves 8 - 10

INGREDIENTS
1 cup panko breadcrumbs, 1 large onion , grated
1 kg / 2 lb beef mince (ground beef), preferably not lean + 2 eggs + 3 garlic cloves (minced) + 1 tsp Worcestershire Sauce + 1/4 cup tomato ketchup + 1/4 cup chopped parsley (optional  or 2 tsp dried parsley or basil) + 1 tsp dried thyme + 2 beef bouillon cubes crumbled or 2 tsp granulated beef + 1 tsp black pepper
GLAZE: 1/2 cup tomato ketchup + 2 tbsp cider vinegar + 1 tbsp brown sugar , lightly packed
.
DIRECTIONS
1. Preheat oven to 180C/350F. Oil or spray a loaf tin very well. 
2. Glaze: Mix together in a small bowl. 
3. Meatloaf: Place breadcrumbs in a very large bowl. Grate over onion. Mix so the breadcrumbs are all wet (trick for ultra tender meatloaf + adds great flavour w/out cooking onion separately).
4. Add remaining ingredients. Mix well using your hands. Form into a loaf shape, pinching together then smoothing over creases and cracks (helps prevent cracks during baking).
5. Transfer into loaf tin. Brush generously with glaze, using about 1/2. Bake for 45 min. Remove from oven, if there’s excess oil on surface pour it off. Brush with most of the remaining glaze.
6. Bake for a further 30 minutes. Remove from oven. Stand for 10 minutes before turning out and cutting into thick slices. Ideal served with a dollop of ketchup, creamy mashed potatoes or mashed cauliflower (see website for recipes!) and steamed vegetables.

Jambalaya | Serves 5 (generously!) 707 cal

1 tbsp vegetable oil, 180g / 6oz bacon (preferably SMOKED) chopped, 200g/ 7oz andouille or smoked sausage sliced*, 300g/ 10 oz chicken thigh 2.5cm /1" pieces, 12 prawns/shrimp , raw, large
4 garlic cloves minced, 1 tbsp (15g) butter, 1 large onion diced, 2 celery ribs & 2 green capsicum/peppers cut into 1.5 cm / 0.5" pieces
1.25 cups long grain rice*, 2.5 cups (625ml) chicken broth / stock (full salt), 200g / 6.5oz crushed canned tomato, 2 tbsp tomato paste
1 cup green onions sliced
CAJUN SPICE MIX: 2 tsp fresh thyme (or 1 tsp dried), 4 tsp sweet paprika, 1 tsp EACH garlic & onion powder, 1/2 tsp EACH cayenne powder (adjust spice to taste), black pepper, salt

1. Heat in oil in a very large ovenproof skillet or dutch oven^ over medium high heat. Cook bacon and sausage until golden, remove. Cook chicken until golden, add to bacon bowl. Sear prawns/shrimp 1.5 min each side, remove to separate bowl.
2. Melt butter, cook garlic, onion, celery and capsicum 5 min or until soft. 
3. Stir in rice, then add broth, canned tomato, tomato paste Spices. Stir well to dissolve, add bacon/saus/chicken. When bubbles appear across most of the surface, give it one last stir, push all rice under liquid surface, then bake 30 min at 180C/350F^.
4. Take out of oven – rice should be 99% cooked (or already cooked). Add prawns/shrimp and green onion, stir through quickly but gently. Cover, return to oven for just 3 min.
5. Serve with more green onions!
.
* Andouille is a spicy really smoky sausage, can’t find it anywhere in Syd. Very close match is polish sausages (kielbasa etc) from Polish/European delis – ask for the most smoky one. Next best is kransky or chorizo and use SMOKED paprika (instead of normal) and make sure to use SMOKED bacon. You can get kranksy at Aussie supermarkets.
^ Shallow pot in video is cast iron @chasseurau 30 cm / 12”, 2.5L/2.5qt. Can also use large dutch oven. BAKING is the safest, foolproof way to make Jambalaya – no burnt base, no gluey mushy rice from over stirring.

node.text:
The secret to EXTRA CRISPY corn fritters? Cornflour and parmesan!!

PS Glad you guys are enjoying the music on these quicker recipe reels. How’s our choice on this one?? 🎶🕺🏻 - N x ❤️

Extra Crispy Corn Fritters
.
INGREDIENTS
1/4 cup plain flour, 1/4 cup cornflour/cornstarch, 1/4 tsp baking soda, 1 egg, 2 tbsp milk, 2 cups fresh corn kernels, raw (canned or frozen ok*), 1/2 cup parmesan finely grated, 3/4 cup spring onions, sliced, 1/2 cup coriander/cilantro, roughly chopped
For cooking:
1/2 cup vegetable oil, Oil spray
Serving: Sour cream, avocado sauce (see note) or ketchup (don’t judge until you’ve tried it) 

METHOD
1. Mix flour, cornflour and baking soda in a bowl,. Add egg and milk, mix until incorporated (batter will be lumpy). Add corn, parmesan, spring onions and coriander. Mix until all the corn is evenly coated in batter.
2. Heat enough oil in non stick skillet so it covers the base over medium high heat. Spray the underside of a spatula with oil (so batter won’t stick when you flatten). Place 1/4 cup batter into skillet, then flatten to 1cm/ 2/5” thick. Repeat with 2 or 3 more, but don’t crowd the skillet.
3. Cook 3 min until deep golden and crisp, then flip and cook the other side for 2 – 3 min. Transfer to rack set on a tray, and keep warm in low oven. Repeat with remaining fritters. Serve with sauce of choice for dunking!

* Canned and frozen thawed ok too, dry thoroughly before using. But for flavour, you can’t beat fresh!

This one’s for everyone who had a few too many #LockdownMargs to wash down too much #SpicyAsianFood 🙋🏻‍♀️

I need some GREENS! - N x ❤️

Big, Quick Chicken Salad – the one I make “all the time” (Serves 4)

3 cups store bought roast chicken , shredded (or cook your own)
12 cups cos / romaine lettuce (2 medium, 1 giant) , chopped into bite size pieces (or other leafy greens)
1 cup corn kernels (can, drained - about 2/3 can)
1/2 red onion , finely sliced
300g/ 10oz cherry or grape tomatoes, halved
2 cucumbers , halved then sliced
2 avocados , cut into bite size chunks (or 1 giant one)
150g/ 5oz bacon , cooked then chopped
DRESSING – shake in jar:
2 1/2 tbsp cider vinegar or lemon juice
6 tbsp extra virgin olive oil
1 garlic clove , minced using garlic press (~1 tsp)
1 tsp Dijon Mustard (or any smooth, non spicy mustard, optional)
2 tsp dried mixed herbs or 1 tbsp fresh (eg dill, chives, parsley, basil)
1 tsp sugar , optional*
3/4 tsp salt, 1/2 tsp black pepper

* Touch of sugar takes sharp edge off vinegar so you can use less oil without dressing being too sour. Can omit if you don’t mind sharp dressing or use more oil.

1. Put all salad ingredients except bacon in a giant bowl. Drizzle with dressing, toss, sprinkle with bacon. Devour!

#recipetineats #semi-detox #chickensalad #eatyourgreens
